{
    "analysis": "From the previous step the telemetry files were successfully loaded and summarized. metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv show full 30-minute per-minute coverage (timestamps from 2022-03-21 02:00 to 02:29 UTC+8). error_logs.csv contains repeated warning messages concentrated on frontend pods (frontend-0/1/2) starting at 02:00:06 UTC+8. This suggests frontend pods are suspect, but we must follow the preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> root cause localization workflow. According to the rules, global thresholds must be calculated using the full available series before filtering to the incident window. Therefore the next necessary step is to calculate global thresholds for metric time series so we can later detect anomalies inside the 02:00–02:30 window. No metric-level anomaly detection has been performed yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full metric.csv series in the kernel, compute global thresholds for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name): specifically calculate the P95 and P5 percentiles and the sample count for each pair. Store the thresholds table in a kernel variable named metric_thresholds. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) showing columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, p95, p5, sorted by p95 descending (highest p95 first). Also return the global min and max timestamp for metric.csv. Do not print full raw series; only the compact table and the min/max timestamps."
}

{
    "analysis": "The metric global thresholds (P95 and P5) for every (cmdb_id,kpi_name) have been computed and stored in metric_thresholds. Timestamps cover the incident window 2022-03-21 02:00:00 to 02:29:00 (UTC+8). Next we need to detect metric anomalies inside the incident window by comparing each per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) value to its global P95 (for high anomalies) and P5 (for low anomalies). This will narrow candidate faulty components and KPIs for further trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter metric.csv to the incident time window 2022-03-21 02:00:00 (inclusive) through 2022-03-21 02:30:00 (exclusive) in Asia/Shanghai (UTC+8). Using the stored metric_thresholds, for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: sample_count (points in window), count_high (# of points with value >= p95), earliest_high_ts (timestamp of first high anomaly or null), count_low (# of points with value <= p5), earliest_low_ts (timestamp of first low anomaly or null), and total_anoms = count_high + count_low. Save this result as metric_anomalies in the kernel. Return two compact outputs only: 1) Top 20 rows of metric_anomalies sorted by total_anoms desc with columns cmdb_id, kpi_name, sample_count, count_high, earliest_high_ts, count_low, earliest_low_ts, total_anoms. 2) Top 10 cmdb_id components ranked by their summed total_anoms (component_total_anoms) with columns cmdb_id, component_total_anoms. Do not print full time series." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global threshold calculation for metrics and detected metric anomalies inside the incident window (2022-03-21 02:00–02:30). The metric anomalies point to two main candidate groups: (1) shippingservice2-0 container/node metrics (many container.node-5 KPIs flagged, though some flags appear spurious due to identical P95/P5), and (2) adservice / adservice2 and several frontend pods which show very high aggregated anomaly counts. Error logs earlier show repeated warnings concentrated in frontend-0/1/2 starting at 02:00:06 UTC+8, indicating user-facing problems. According to the diagnosis workflow, we should now use trace analysis to (a) narrow which service/pod in the call chain is actually faulty (the root cause should be the most-downstream faulty component in traces), and (b) correlate trace anomalies with frontend error logs and metric anomalies. We do not yet have global thresholds for trace features, nor have we checked which traces show anomalies in the incident window. The next step is to compute trace-level global thresholds across the full trace.csv and then detect anomalies for the incident window to produce a ranked list of candidate faulty trace metrics and components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full trace.csv in the kernel, compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) and sample counts for each (cmdb_id, trace_name). Save the result as trace_thresholds. Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 02:00:00 (inclusive) through 2022-03-21 02:30:00 (exclusive) in Asia/Shanghai (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in the window compute: sample_count (points in window), count_high (# of points with value >= p95), earliest_high_ts (timestamp of first high anomaly or null), count_low (# of points with value <= p5), earliest_low_ts (timestamp of first low anomaly or null), and total_anoms = count_high + count_low. Save as trace_anomalies. Return only two compact outputs: 1) Top 20 rows of trace_anomalies sorted by total_anoms desc with columns cmdb_id, trace_name, sample_count, count_high, earliest_high_ts, count_low, earliest_low_ts, total_anoms. 2) Top 10 cmdb_id components ranked by summed total_anoms (component_total_anoms) with columns cmdb_id, component_total_anoms. Do not print full raw time series." }

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global thresholds and detected anomalies for metrics and traces within the incident window. Metric anomalies highlighted large aggregated anomaly counts on adservice/adservice2 and frontend pods, and many container/node KPIs for shippingservice2-0 (some of which appear to be threshold artifacts where P95==P5). Trace anomalies concentrate on frontend-related traces (trace.from_frontend* and trace.self/error_rate) and on checkout/cart traces. Error logs show repeated warning messages on frontend-0/1/2 beginning at 02:00:06 UTC+8. To localize the root cause we must (1) determine which trace flows exhibit the earliest and most significant anomalies originating from frontends, and (2) correlate those timestamps with the frontend error_logs. The next atomic step is to extract frontend-origin traces from the already-computed trace_anomalies to find the earliest trace anomaly times and affected downstream components; this will give candidate root-cause components and exact occurrence times to correlate with logs and metrics.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the trace_anomalies kernel table, filter rows where trace_name contains 'from_frontend' or 'from_frontend2'. Return the top 20 rows sorted by earliest_high_ts ascending (earliest first). Include columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, sample_count, count_high, earliest_high_ts, count_low, earliest_low_ts, total_anoms. Also return a compact aggregate: for each unique cmdb_id in that filtered set, compute the earliest earliest_high_ts (per component) and the sum of total_anoms; return the top 10 components sorted by earliest_high_ts ascending (show cmdb_id, component_earliest_high_ts, component_total_anoms). Keep outputs bounded to these two results only." }

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global thresholds and detected anomalies across metrics and traces for the incident window. The telemetry shows: repeated frontend warning logs starting at 02:00:06+08; pervasive trace anomalies with earliest_high_ts at 02:00:00+08 across many downstream services; and metric anomalies concentrated on adservice/adservice2 and some shippingservice2-0 node/container KPIs (some of which look like threshold artifacts because p95≈p5). Because many thresholds are degenerate (p95==p5 or values nearly constant), we cannot trust naive per-point anomaly flags. To localize the root cause we should focus on real, significant deviations in trace values originating from frontend calls during the earliest minutes of the window and correlate these with frontend error_logs. Therefore we must inspect trace values in the immediate startup window (02:00:00–02:05:00) for traces named trace.from_frontend* / trace.from_frontend2* and compare their short-window mean to their global thresholds to find truly significant deviations (not just degenerate p95/p5 artifacts). This will help identify which downstream component first experienced a meaningful anomaly and the exact occurrence minute to correlate with frontend logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace_thresholds and the full trace.csv in the kernel, filter trace.csv to timestamps within 2022-03-21 02:00:00 (inclusive) through 2022-03-21 02:05:00 (exclusive) Asia/Shanghai (UTC+8). Further filter rows where trace_name contains 'from_frontend' or 'from_frontend2'. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: sample_count (in this 5-min window), mean_value, p95, p5 (from trace_thresholds), earliest_high_ts (first timestamp in the window with value >= p95 or null), earliest_low_ts (first timestamp in the window with value <= p5 or null). Compute deviation_ratio as max(mean_value / p95 if p95>0 else NaN, p5 / mean_value if mean_value>0 else NaN) to capture how far mean departs from thresholds. Select rows where mean_value >= p95*1.2 or mean_value <= p5*0.8 (i.e., >=20% deviation). Return: 1) Top 20 rows matching this condition sorted by deviation_ratio desc with columns cmdb_id, trace_name, sample_count, mean_value, p95, p5, earliest_high_ts, earliest_low_ts, deviation_ratio. 2) A single-line summary count of how many (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs met the condition. Keep outputs compact." }

{
    "analysis": "You inspected frontend-origin traces in the early 5-minute window and found 79 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs whose short-window mean deviated >=20% from global thresholds. The strongest measurable latency deviation among those was adservice-1 trace.from_frontend-0.duration_p95 (earliest_high_ts = 2022-03-21 02:01:00+08). However many trace/error_rate series and other KPIs have degenerate thresholds (p95==p5==0), producing NaNs or unreliable deviation ratios — so these must be treated cautiously. Separately, error_logs.csv already showed repeated warning messages on frontend-0/1/2 beginning at 02:00:06+08. To progress toward root cause localization we need to inspect the actual error log messages in detail (which may name downstream services or network errors) and confirm whether frontend pods themselves report backend call failures. This will help decide whether the root cause is a frontend pod, a downstream service, or a broader network/node issue. No final root cause can be declared yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the error_logs DataFrame in the kernel, filter rows with cmdb_id starting with 'frontend' (frontend, frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0 if present). Produce a compact aggregate table (limit to top 10 rows) grouped by cmdb_id showing: count_of_logs, earliest_log_timestamp, latest_log_timestamp. Also compute the top 5 most frequent message text patterns (or the full message string if few unique) across all frontend logs with their counts. Finally, return the top 20 raw frontend error log rows with columns timestamp, cmdb_id, message to inspect exact message content and any mention of downstream services or network errors. Keep outputs compact and store all full DataFrames in kernel variables for later steps." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps loaded telemetry, computed global thresholds, detected metric and trace anomalies, and found heavy frontend warning logs starting at 02:00:06+08 with the truncated message 'severity: warning, message: failed to retrieve...'. The Executor previously returned only truncated messages and keyword scans that matched only the truncated phrase. The full (untruncated) message payloads were not retrieved due to Executor failure. We need the full message texts to extract downstream targets (service names, URLs, HTTP codes, error types) and to correlate exact timestamps with trace/metric anomalies. At this point we cannot finalize a root cause because the frontend log details are missing and many metric/trace thresholds are degenerate, so further evidence from full logs is required.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the kernel variable frontend_logs_df, return compact, untruncated frontend log text as follows (keep outputs bounded):\n1) Top 20 unique full message strings with their occurrence counts sorted by count descending (columns: message, count). Ensure the 'message' values are the complete, untruncated text stored in the DataFrame.\n2) Up to 50 raw frontend log rows sorted by timestamp ascending (earliest first) with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, message — again ensure the message field is the full text (no truncation).\nDo not compute additional aggregates or searches in this step. Store any full DataFrames in kernel variables for later analysis but only return the two compact results above." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We retrieved full frontend error messages and found the repeated, untruncated message \"severity: warning, message: failed to retrieve ads\" (546 occurrences) beginning at 2022-03-21 02:00:06+08 across frontend-0/1/2. This strongly implicates adservice (the ads provider) or the frontend→adservice call path as the likely failure area. Earlier trace analysis also highlighted an actionable deviation: adservice-1 trace.from_frontend-0.duration_p95 showed a significant increase with earliest_high_ts = 2022-03-21 02:01:00+08. Many metric/trace anomaly flags are noisy due to degenerate thresholds, so we must verify adservice-side signals in metrics and traces within the incident window to identify the earliest meaningful fault and its resource cause. The next step is to inspect metric and trace anomaly summaries already computed for all components but filtered to adservice-related cmdb_ids to determine which adservice pod or service first exhibited a strong anomaly and at what exact minute.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the kernel variables metric_anomalies and trace_anomalies, filter rows where cmdb_id contains 'adservice' (this should include adservice, adservice-0, adservice-1, adservice-2, adservice2, adservice2-0 if present). Return two compact results only: \n1) Top 20 metric_anomalies rows for these cmdb_ids sorted by earliest_high_ts ascending (columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, sample_count, count_high, earliest_high_ts, count_low, earliest_low_ts, total_anoms). \n2) Top 20 trace_anomalies rows for these cmdb_ids sorted by earliest_high_ts ascending (columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, sample_count, count_high, earliest_high_ts, count_low, earliest_low_ts, total_anoms). \nKeep outputs bounded to these tables (max 20 rows each). Store any filtered DataFrames in kernel variables for follow-up but do not print full raw series." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We confirmed frontend pods logged repeated warnings \"failed to retrieve ads\" starting at 2022-03-21 02:00:06+08, strongly implicating adservice or the frontend→adservice path. Trace anomalies for adservice-originating traces show earliest_high_ts at 02:00:00+08 for many series, but many of those flags are likely artifacts from degenerate thresholds (p95≈p5 or zeros). A more reliable signal is the short-window trace deviation we found for adservice-1 (trace.from_frontend-0.duration_p95) with earliest_high_ts = 2022-03-21 02:01:00+08. Metric anomalies point to adservice/adservice2 resource and mesh metrics (CPU, threads, file descriptors, Istio request metrics) with many flags; adservice2-0 file_descriptors had count_high=27 with earliest high at 02:00:00+08, which could indicate resource exhaustion. To progress to root cause localization we need corroborating evidence from adservice logs and targeted raw metric samples for the most suspicious KPIs (e.g., file_descriptors, container_cpu_load, uninterruptible tasks, ulimits max_open_files). The immediate next step is to check normalized logs (log.csv) for adservice-related components within the incident window to see whether adservice reported errors or increased error counts that align with frontend failures.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter log.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 02:00:00 (inclusive) through 2022-03-21 02:30:00 (exclusive) Asia/Shanghai (UTC+8). Then select rows where cmdb_id contains 'adservice' (match adservice, adservice-0, adservice-1, adservice-2, adservice2, adservice2-0). Return two compact outputs only: \n1) Top 20 raw rows sorted by timestamp ascending with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, log_name, value. \n2) An aggregate table per cmdb_id (limit to these adservice cmdb_ids) with columns: cmdb_id, sample_count (rows in the window), max_value (max of value), mean_value, earliest_nonzero_ts (earliest timestamp where value>0 or null if none). \nKeep outputs bounded as specified and store any filtered DataFrames in kernel variables for follow-up." 
}

{
    "analysis": "You inspected adservice metrics and logs in the incident window. Findings so far: frontend pods repeatedly logged “failed to retrieve ads” starting at 2022-03-21 02:00:06+08, strongly implicating calls to adservice. Normalized adservice logs (log.error_count) show zero errors and normal row_count throughput, so the issue may be in the frontend→adservice path (network/mesh) or adservice resource limits not manifesting as application-level errors. Metric_anomalies highlighted adservice/adservice2 Istio/mesh and container/node KPIs with many flags; notably adservice2-0 had container_file_descriptors with count_high=27 (earliest high at 02:00:00+08), suggesting potential resource exhaustion. Trace analysis found a measurable latency deviation for adservice-1 (trace.from_frontend-0.duration_p95) with earliest_high_ts = 2022-03-21 02:01:00+08. However many anomaly flags are noisy due to degenerate thresholds, so we need raw per-minute values to confirm real spikes. We do not yet have a definitive root cause component, exact occurrence minute, or precise reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Return raw per-minute values (compact tables) inside the incident early window to confirm spikes:\n1) From metric.csv, filter rows with cmdb_id == 'adservice2-0' AND kpi_name == 'container.node-6.container_file_descriptors' for timestamps between 2022-03-21 02:00:00 (inclusive) and 2022-03-21 02:05:00 (exclusive) Asia/Shanghai (UTC+8). Return all matching rows with columns timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value (limit to max 20 rows).\n2) From trace.csv, filter rows with cmdb_id == 'adservice-1' AND trace_name IN ['trace.from_frontend-0.duration_p95','trace.from_frontend-0.duration_mean','trace.from_frontend-0.error_rate'] for the same 02:00:00–02:05:00 window. Return all matching rows with columns timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value (limit to max 20 rows).\nOnly return these two compact tables (no further aggregation). Store full filtered DataFrames in kernel variables for follow-up." 
}

